The area

Address
Neighborhood: Midtown
This is the iconic New York that so many visitors imagine before they visit - spectacular skyscrapers like the Chrysler Building and Empire State Building, iconic public buildings like Grand Central Terminal and the New York Public Library, and the non-stop hustle and bustle of the city streets. Fifth Avenue is a shopper's paradise where you can find every kind of store imaginable, with fashion brands ranging from the affordable to the ultra-fancy. Visit Rockefeller Center to experience towering Art Deco grandeur, and foodies will love the busy restaurants that stay open late in Koreatown. After dark, Midtown calms down a bit, but at any time of day or night it still feels 100% New York.
How to get there
  • 5th Ave / 53rd St • 4 min walk
  • 47–50 Sts – Rockefeller Center • 5 min walk

Insulting offering by Saks Customer Service for a broken item
Oct 2024 • Solo
It's best to avoid purchasing low-value but fragile items from Saks' online store. I ordered a $65 ornament along with other products to qualify for a promotion where spending $3,000 would earn a $900 gift card. However, the ornament arrived broken, wrapped only in thin plastic without any protective box. When I reached out to customer service via text and provided a photo of the damaged item, they informed me that I could get a $65 refund, but this would cause me to lose the $300 difference in the gift card value, as my purchase total would no longer meet the $3,000 threshold, dropping it to the $2,000 level with a $600 gift card. I then called their phone support, hoping for a better resolution. The response was the same, though they offered a 10% discount on the broken item, effectively a $6.50 refund if I kept it without requesting a full refund. Weighing the potential $300 gift card loss against the $65 refund, I opted not to pursue the refund and retain the original $900 gift card. More importantly, I declined the $6.50 "compensation" from Saks, finding it to be insulting. It was a very disappointing experience—I ended up with a broken $65 ornament and spent an hour dealing with customer service for an unsatisfactory resolution.
Written October 23, 2024

Aug 2024 • Solo
I ordered a dress in August to wear to a wedding. Upon receiving the dress in the mail I could immediately tell that the dress had been worn. It smelled so strongly of body odor I couldn’t even try it on. It was a strapless dress and the garment loops had been cut out of it as well. The dress was also supposed to come with removable spaghetti straps that you could add to the dress if you’d like and there was only one strap included. I immediately called Saks customer service to let them know that they had sent me a damaged/worn dress that I assume someone has previously returned (after they wore it to an event)!! The gentleman apologized and asked that I email him pictures of the cut out garment loops, which I did and said that I could return the dress and that I’d be refunded in 7-10 business days. Well, during this time Saks apparently changed their refund policy which allows them up to 30 days to refund you. It has now been 30 days since they received the damaged dress back at their warehouse and I just spoke to a customer service representative and they have YET to even process my return! From someone who has always loved Saks, this is absolutely ridiculous and I will never shop at Saks again.

citychic
New York, NY20 contributions
Disappointing
Jul 2024 • Solo
While the iridescent accents on the center of the first floor are visually stunning, the store looks dark and stuffy and the shopping experience leaves much to be desired.

The Chanel concession on the first floor is hit or miss. The selection is plentiful, yes, but what good is the selection when the service is woefully inconsistent? Sometimes you receive terrific, warm service and sometimes it’s awful. Why is it like this? Getting anyone to pick up their phones or return texts is impossible (forget trying the store’s main number to get to the Chanel store - been disconnected multiple times - why?). Found a lovely sales lady at Dior that made sure I had a nice experience.

It’s odd to have beauty on the second floor; I can’t get used to it. It was so much better on the main floor but I guess that ship has sailed. Perplexing was the two bathroom stalls in the ladies restroom (the kindest thing to say about it: “industrial chic”) which almost always ensures a long line.

Most disappointing was the much-publicized jewelry floor (one floor below street level). The lack of selection was frankly shocking and the floor looked very austere for the location. So much wasted valuable real estate. The fine jewelry section at Bergdorf is far, far superior. I’d suggest moving beauty back to this floor and jewelry to the second floor.
Written August 8, 2024

I opened a claim with Saks. A few days later, Saks told me there was nothing they could do because they checked the video of their distribution center, and the perfume was put in the box in the distribution center. This doesn't change the fact that the package was cut open and looted before it arrived. Instead of taking ownership of the issue by saying they would refund me or send me a new perfume and take care of figuring out what happened and filing a claim with the delivery company or otherwise handling through their normal process, as a "luxury" department store should, their only response (from multiple customer service reps) was that I should file a police report with my local police department. Excuse me, what??? Are you kidding me? Filing a police report for something like this is useless at best, and it puts responsibility on me for something totally out of my control. I've never had such a poor experience with a company ever.
